TOPIC: SET BASICS (5)

    Vocabs:
    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    + Set: unordered collection of unique elements.
    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    Properties of a set ->
        + Elements are unordered. Elements in the set do not have a position or index.
        + Elements are unique. No elements in the set share the same value.

    Creating a set -> set()
        + Accepts a sequence type iterable object (list, tuple, string, etc.)
        + Set literal can be written using curly braces { } with commas separating set elements.
        + An empty set can be created using set().

        Example:
            Create set with set() function -> nums1 = set([1, 2, 3])        Output: {1, 2, 3}
            Create set using set literal   -> nums2 = {7, 8, 9}             Output: {7, 8, 9}

!!! Because the elements of a set are unordered and have no meaningful position, the index operator is not valid !!!

- A set is often used to reduce a list of items that potentially contains duplicates into a collection of unique values.
- Simply passing a list into set() will cause any duplicates to be omitted in the created set.

    Modifying sets ->
        + Sets are mutable - elements can be added or removed using set methods.

    Function          | Purpose
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    len(set)          | Find the length (number of elements) of the set.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set1.update(set2) | Adds the elements in set2 to set1.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set.add(value)    | Adds value into the set.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set.remove(value) | Removes value from the set. Raises KeyError if value is not found.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set.pop()         | Removes a random element from the set.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set.clear()       | Clears all elements from the set.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    Set Operations ->
        Python set objects support typical set theory operations such as intersections and unions.

    Operation                                | Purpose
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set.intersection(set_a, set_b, set_c...) | Returns a new set containing only the elements in common between set and
                                             | all provided sets.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set.union(set_a, set_b, set_c...)        | Returns a new set containing all of the unique elements in all sets.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set.difference(set_a, set_b, set_c...)   | Returns a set containing only the elements of set that are not found in
                                               any of the provided sets.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    set_a.symmetric_difference(set_b)        | Returns a set containing only elements that appear in exactly one of
                                               set_a or set_b.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

