TOPIC: COMMON DATA TYPES

    TYPE   | NOTES: NUMERIC DATA TYPES
    -----------------------------------------------------------
    int    | Numeric: Used for variable-width integers
    -----------------------------------------------------------
    float  | Numeric: Used for floating-point numbers


    SEQUENCE TYPE NOTES
        + string, list, tuples are containers of collections of objects ordered by position where it can be
          accessed with index.
        + list is mutable and individual elements may be edited or removed.
        + tuple is immutable and individual elements may not be edited or removed.
            - list and tuple can contain any type.
            - can apply len() and element indexing using brackets []
        + dictionary serves as a container. Each element is independent having no special ordering or relation
          to other elements. Dictionary uses key-value pairs to associate a key with a value.

    TYPE   | NOTES: SEQUENCE and MAPPING TYPES
    -----------------------------------------------------------
    string | Sequence: Used for text
    -----------------------------------------------------------
    list   | Sequence: mutable container with ordered elements
    -----------------------------------------------------------
    tuple  | Sequence: Immutable container with ordered elements
    -----------------------------------------------------------
    set    | Set: mutable container with unordered and unique elements
    -----------------------------------------------------------
    dictionary | Mapping: container with key-values assoc. elements

CHOOSING CONTAINER TYPE

    LIST -> when data has an order, such as lines of text on a page

    TUPLE -> if contained data should not change.

    DICTIONARY -> if order is not important, capture relationships between elements such as
                  student names and grades.

